## 6. Training targets

The candidate-aware target design is correct and one of the strongest parts of the plan. The rule “unsampled legal pair != negative pair” is essential. In a sampled pair-action space, omitted actions are unknown, not false. The plan explicitly requires pruned candidate-set posteriors, completed-Q or regularized posteriors, marginal targets, conditional targets, sampled-softmax/ranking losses with proposal correction, tactical auxiliaries, and value/Q heads. 

The marginal and conditional auxiliary targets are helpful if they are derived from the pruned joint posterior and do not become independent policy targets. They are dangerous if:

* marginal targets are trained from raw pair counts that include forced exploration;
* conditional targets use only canonical ordering;
* completion targets punish unadmitted second cells as negatives;
* terminal-equivalent filler cells create arbitrary preferences.

The plan’s terminal-equivalence handling is conceptually right: if one cell wins, then every legal pair containing that cell may be strategically equivalent, so the model should not learn arbitrary second-cell preferences. 

I would add one more target status:

```text
pair_policy_complete = false
support_type = admitted_candidate_set_without_explicit_negatives
```

This should be the default unless the target builder can prove exhaustive support, explicit sampled negatives, or completed-Q posterior semantics. That prevents future code from accidentally treating a sparse candidate list as a full distribution.

