## 7. Tactical design

Terminal-only tactical V1 is the right scope. Exact wins, exact blocks, terminal-equivalent pairs, and impossible-to-block flags are cheap, testable, and necessary. Overloads, forks, shared pivots, and bounded tactical races are important, but they are also a major source of complexity and oracle bias. Deferring them to V2 is correct as long as V1 is not judged by “superhuman tactical strength” prematurely. 

The plan preserves the right structure for the model to learn tactics without a large tactical oracle: `WINDOW6` objects, legal-cell/window membership, window overlap, shared cover cells, same-axis/same-line relations, and active-window cap telemetry. The plan correctly treats six-cell windows as the minimal tactical object matching the win condition. 

My caveat: terminal-only V1 may not be enough to bootstrap non-terminal forcing play. The answer is not to add a giant oracle immediately. The better V1 addition is **evaluation-only non-terminal tactical suites**: overload fixtures, fork fixtures, shared-pivot fixtures, and bounded hot-window-race positions used to measure whether the model and search are learning them. Do not use these as hard filters or default proposal sources until V1 candidate recall and runtime are proven.

